”—Michael Kwass, Johns Hopkins University Ashli White analyzes the circulation of objects associated with the American, French, and Haitian revolutions, arguing that the ideals of the Atlantic revolutions were contested not just in texts but also through objects. She considers how, as revolutionary things traveled from one site in the Atlantic to another, they brought people into contact with these political movements in visceral, multiple, and provocative ways. Focusing on a wide range of objects with transnational reach—ceramics and furniture, garments and accessories, prints, maps, and public amusements—she draws out the political impact of material culture for diverse populations. Enslaved and free, women and men, poor, middling, and elite—all turned to objects as a means to realize their varied, and sometimes competing, visions of revolutionary change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMaterial culturexPolitical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy18th century. 0aMaterial culturexPolitical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical culturezAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical culturezAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aRevolutionsxHistoryy18th century. 0aRevolutionsxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074